# Design System

Decor ships two design systems side by side — Daisy (daisyUI semantic palette) and Suite (bespoke tokens). Pick the skin per surface; you can mix them in the same app.

## Daisy skin

Daisy uses [daisyUI's semantic colour system](https://daisyui.com/docs/colors/), so the look of every component adapts to whichever daisyUI theme is set on `<html data-theme="...">`.

### Colours

- **Brand**: `primary`, `secondary`, `accent`
- **Feedback**: `success`, `warning`, `error`, `info`
- **Neutral**: `base`, `neutral`, with surfaces in `base-100` / `base-200` / `base-300`

```ruby
render Decor::Daisy::Notification.new(title: "Saved", color: :success)
render Decor::Daisy::Button.new(label: "Submit", color: :primary)
render Decor::Daisy::Badge.new(label: "Beta", color: :info)
```

### Typography & spacing

Daisy components use Tailwind's default type scale (`text-xs` → `text-xl`) and spacing scale. Component-specific sizing goes through the shared `size` prop (`:xs`, `:sm`, `:md`, `:lg`, `:xl`).

### Themes

Any daisyUI theme works — components adapt via daisyUI's CSS custom properties.

```html
<html data-theme="light">
<html data-theme="dark">
<html data-theme="cyberpunk">
```

## Suite skin

Suite ships its own design tokens that don't depend on daisyUI's palette. Tokens are defined in `app/assets/tailwind/decor.css` and prefixed `--color-suite-*`, `--radius-suite-*`, `--duration-suite-*`.

### Colours

Numbered shade scale (50–900) for each semantic family:

- `suite-primary-{50,100,200,…,900}`
- `suite-success-{50…900}`
- `suite-warning-{50…900}`
- `suite-danger-{50…900}`
- `suite-gray-{25,…}` — extra-light surface tint
- `suite-hairline`, `suite-hairline-strong` — 8% / 12% black hairline borders

Use the numbered shades directly (Suite components reference them, e.g. `decor:bg-suite-primary-50`, `decor:text-suite-danger-700`). Consumers can override Suite tokens at the `@theme` layer to retheme the suite.

### Radius

- `rounded-suite-card` (10px) — applied to card surfaces, modals, settings rows
- `rounded-suite-control` (6px) — applied to buttons, inputs, chips

### Motion

- `duration-suite-fast` (120ms) — hover transitions, small state changes
- `duration-suite-base` (200ms) — modal in/out, popovers

### Typography

Type utilities bundle size, weight, leading, and tracking. The caller still sets colour separately:

- `suite-section-title`
- `suite-subsection-title`
- `suite-label`
- `suite-body`
- `suite-dense-body`
- `suite-description`
- `suite-caption`

```ruby
render Decor::Suite::Avatar.new(initials: "JG", color: :alt2)
render Decor::Suite::Button.new(label: "Submit", color: :primary, style: :filled)
render Decor::Suite::Modals::Modal.new(id: "m", title: "Confirm", variant: :destructive)
```

## Shared prop conventions

Both skins share these props via `Decor::Components::*` abstract bases.

### `size`

`:xs`, `:sm`, `:md`, `:lg`, `:xl` (with aliases `:small` → `:sm`, etc.). A handful of components redefine the set (e.g. `:wide` / `:link` on buttons); those are noted in the component reference.

### `color`

For Daisy, maps to daisyUI's semantic palette. For Suite, maps to the numbered shade scale at the canonical weight (usually `-500` for filled, `-50/100` for backgrounds).

### `style`

`:filled`, `:outlined`, `:ghost` is the default set. Some components redefine it (e.g. Tabs uses `:bordered` / `:lifted` / `:boxed` / `:ghost`).

## Accessibility

Components include ARIA attributes where they own the chrome (e.g. `role="tablist"` on Tabs, `aria-label` on icon-only buttons, `aria-describedby` on modals). Keyboard navigation and focus management are implemented in the paired Stimulus controllers.

## Configuring the default skin

`Decor.default_skin` controls the skin that view helpers like `decor_flash` use. Default `:daisy`. Set it once in an initializer:

```ruby
Decor.configure do |c|
  c.default_skin = :suite
end
```
